    "2 Mind map of abuse and malicious applications of GenAI and large language models Table 22Examples of intentional malicious deployments of LLMs and GenAI in the real worldProof-of-conceptInputting a prompt like \"Write a 2000-word essayon the impact of the Industrial Revolution onEuropean society\" into an LLM and receiving adetailed, well-structured essay in returnFeeding an LLM a prompt such as \"Generate aresearch paper on the effects of a drug called'Zyphorin' on Alzheimer's disease\" and obtaininga seemingly legitimate paperInputting \"Generate a tweet in the style of [Celeb-rity Name] discussing climate change\" and gettinga fabricated tweet that appears genuineInputting \"Generate a propaganda article promot-ing the benefits of a fictional government policy'GreenFuture Initiative\"' and receiving a detailedarticlePrompting an LLM with \"Generate a letter fromNapoleon Bonaparte to Josephine discussing hisstrategies for the Battle of Waterloo\" to produce afabricated historical documentGoal Application ExampleDishonesty Automated essay writing and academic dishonesty Students could use LLMs to generate essays,research papers, or assignments, bypassing thelearning process and undermining academicintegrityGenerating fake research papers LLMs can be used to produce fake research paperswith fabricated data, results, and references,potentially polluting academic databases ormisleading researchersPropaganda Impersonating celebrities or public figures LLMs can generate statements, tweets, or mes-sages that mimic the style of celebrities or publicfigures, leading to misinformation or defamationAutomated propaganda generation Governments or organizations could use LLMs toproduce propaganda material at scale, targetingdifferent demographics or regions with tailoredmessagesCreating Fake Historical Documents or Texts LLMs can be used to fabricate historical docu-ments, letters, or texts, potentially misleadinghistorians or altering public perception of eventsJournal of Computational Social Science (2024) 7:549-569 Table 33Proof-of-concept Scenarios Highlighting the Potential for Different Type of Harms in Malicious GenAI ApplicationsProof-of-conceptDeploying an LLM to manage hundreds ofTwitter accounts, all pushing a specificpolitical agenda or spreading misinformationabout a public health issueAsking an LLM to \"Provide natural remediesfor a heart condition\" and receiving poten-tially harmful or ineffective suggestionsInputting \"Create an advertisement for a fic-tional skincare product that provides instantresults\" and obtaining a misleading ad thatpromises unrealistic outcomesPrompting an LLM with \"Generate a quarterlyfinancial report for a fictional tech company'TechNova' showing a X% profit increase\"to obtain a detailed but fabricated financialdocumentAsking an LLM to \"Create a script for a callclaiming to be from the IRS, notifying therecipient of unpaid taxes\" to produce aconvincing scam scriptExampleLLMs can be used to operate multiple socialmedia accounts, creating an illusion ofgrassroots movements or artificially ampli-fying certain narrativesLLMs can produce misleading medical infor-mation, potentially endangering individualswho might act on this false adviceLLMs can be used to generate advertise-ments that exaggerate product capabilitiesor make false claimsLLMs can be used to generate false financialdata or reports, potentially misleadinginvestors or manipulating stock pricesLLMs can produce scripts for scam calls,making them sound more genuine andincreasing the likelihood of deceivingindividualsApplicationAutomated social media manipulationGenerating fake medical advice or informa-tionCrafting deceptive advertisementsCreating fake financial reports or dataGenerating scripts for scam callsHarmInfo."
